Polish Stocks: Budimex, Lotos, Orlen, Synthos, TPSA, Zachodni

-- B y   P a w e l   K o z l o w s k i   a n d   M o n i k a   R o z l a l
-- 
2011-07-27T16:13:48Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-27/polish-stocks-budimex-lotos-orlen-synthos-tpsa-zachodni.html
Poland ’s <a href="blpnews:linkid=Y4I1JVTKQZXF">WIG20 Index</a> fell for a
third day, losing 31.33, or 1.2 percent, to close at 2,689.21.  The following are among the most active stocks on the
 Warsaw Stock Exchange  today. Stock symbols follow company names.  <a href="blpnews:linkid=WJOO786LR2Q5"> Budimex SA (BDX) </a&gt fell for a third consecutive day,
losing 0.8 zloty, or 1 percent, to 80.2 zloty. Poland’s biggest
construction company said first-half net income fell to 119.8
million zloty from 126.6 million zloty a year earlier.  <a href="blpnews:linkid=45Y9VFQGKHRG">PKN Orlen SA</a> (PKN PW), Poland’s biggest oil company,
slumped 1 zloty, or 2.1 percent, to 46 zloty. <a href="blpnews:linkid=67WBNS5KRLB4"> Grupa Lotos SA (LTS) </a&gt, the second-largest refiner, declined 0.7 zloty, or 1.8
percent, to 38.8 zloty, a second day of decreases. Oil fell on
speculation rising U.S. crude stockpiles indicate fuel demand is
faltering in the world’s biggest consumer of the commodity.  <a href="blpnews:linkid=OPFJLS5Z75GS">Synthos SA</a> (SNS PW) increased 0.02 zloty, or 0.4 percent,
to 5.74 zloty. The chemical producer controlled by Polish
billionaire Michal Solowow had its price estimate raised to 6.41
zloty from 5.13 zloty at ING Groep NV.  <a href="blpnews:linkid=237TUMFDOSMM"> Telekomunikacja Polska SA (TPS) </a&gt climbed 0.4 zloty, or
2.4 percent, to 17 zloty, the highest close this month. Poland’s
biggest phone company will propose using 800 million zloty, or
about half it received from the sale of TP Emitel Sp. z o.o.
unit, for a share buyback.  Separately, first-half net income rose to 1.18 billion
zloty from 609 million zloty a year earlier. That compares with
the 971.7 million-zloty mean estimate of 10 analysts surveyed by
Bloomberg.  <a href="blpnews:linkid=741DWPKVSF8U"> Bank Zachodni WBK SA (BZW) </a&gt jumped 7.5 zloty, or 3.3
percent, to 234.5 zloty, rising for the first time in eight
days. Poland’s third-biggest bank by market value and a unit of
Banco Santander SA said first-half net income rose to 641.1
million zloty from 483.6 million zloty a year earlier. That
exceeded the 601.5 million-zloty mean estimate of seven analysts
surveyed by Bloomberg News.  To contact the reporter on this story:
